^d@e@2hondo717: now, let us talk about why it is important to bid correctly, and how partner @E@3 takes certain inferences from what you bid or do not bid.  For example in this hand East bid stayman, promising at least one 4 card major. Since East bid 3@D, there is no reason for East to show a 4 card major.  So if she bids she bid hearts at after 3@D that must be 5 hearts and 4 spades. Because if East just had 5 hearts and not 4 spades, she would have simply transferred to hearts by bidding 3@D.   If the auction went 2N-3@C-3@D-3@H, East is showing 5@H and 4@S. To say it differently, in response to NT if you have 5/4 major you bid Stayman first then show your five cards major. The point is expert partners take inferences by what you did and did not. 
 
 hondo717: Let me talk about "negative inferences" in the bidding.  Expert partners infer things about their pard's hand by what they did not bid as well as what they did bid.  Here is a very simple example.   Say I open 1D and partner bids 1N.  Because pard DID NOT bid 1H or 1S, I know pard cannot have a 4 card major. “Negative inferences” are very important, and it is why you must always strive to make the correct bid.



